Quite a few stores down town and the one on M street is convient to me. It's on a corner and has a wide side walk with a place to park my bike or scooter. It'd bright spacious and clean. It's has lots of normal coffee in thermos along one wall. Light, dark and decaffeinated all the usual milks and creams. The opposite wall is sandwiches and soups and interesting things like cheese and colliflour etc. Good breads.  Infront is the counter where you can get pastries and expresso and latte,  tea etc. The shop opens up to areas to sit at table and beach like seats along one wall. Big windows offer views of street activity. There are two well appointed spacious bathrooms. You need a code from the counter to access. A place to eat a good sandwich and coffee and read your book for a while. They point out that at the end of the day what food is unsold is given to charity or homeless. It's a nice sanctuary in walking distance of lots of down town.

One of the larger Pret A Manger locations and has comfortable, non-distracting seating. Great for working with a laptop. I often drop by and grab the quinoa breakfast bowls (gluten free) and am never disappointed. The rest of their grab-and-go food always looks fresh and delicious. If you become a frequent customer, check out their app too! They have better deals and coupons than most other coffee shops around.

I love how nice the staff here are, but the Pret on L st is definitely way more professional. I ordered a ice latte with extra espresso shot and they got my order wrong. In stead of making a new one, I saw a staff whispering to the barista and they poured the extra hot latte directly over ice, added some coffee and handed it to me. If you pay bare minimum respect to the qualities of your drinks, you really shouldn't do that. I paid extra for the extra espresso and a stronger taste but ended up getting a latte that was way way way more watery than the original one. Not the first time my order got messed up. Will definitely detour for the L st one in the future.

Located in various sites around Washington DC, and elsewhere, they offer relatively affordable, wholesome and fresh quick and easy food. They are my go-to for lunch especially.  One demerit for the obnoxiously loud and limited choice of music in most DC locations . For those of us north of 45, blaring hip-hop doesn't cut it, nor the techno-flavored offerings. More variety and yes, something from the golden era of music - the 20th century- would round this place out. Otherwise it's too self-consciously "hip" and overly brash and modern. Nothing mellow ever? All millenial, all the time? It certainly may get people in and out fast.

When i used to feel very welcome here. Its Sad, why mess with a good thing? New management maybe? I hope this is not the new model for the franchise and that they leave other locations alone.
